05067nam a22007575i 9780813576886DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135768867 a10.36019/97808135768862doi  a(DE-B1597)529478  a(OCoLC)987911279  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aGT2853.U5bF565 2017eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a394.1/209732231 aFinn, S. Margot, eauthor.10aDiscriminating Taste :bHow Class Anxiety Created the American Food Revolution /cS. Margot Finn. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b10 photographs, 5 graphs, 2 diagrams  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Discriminating Taste -- t1. Incompatible Standards: Th e Four Ideals of the Food Revolution -- t2. Aspirational Eating: Food and Status Anxiety in the Gilded Age and the Progressive Era -- t3. No Culinary Enlightenment: Why Everything You Know about Food Is Wrong -- t4. Anyone Can Cook: Saying Yes to Meritocracy -- t5. Just Mustard: Negotiating with Food Snobbery -- t6. Feeling Good about Where You Shop: Sacrifice, Pleasure, and Virtue -- tConclusion: Confronting the Soft Bigotry of Taste -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor the past four decades, increasing numbers of Americans have started paying greater attention to the food they eat, buying organic vegetables, drinking fine wines, and seeking out exotic cuisines. Yet they are often equally passionate about the items they refuse to eat: processed foods, generic brands, high-carb meals. While they may care deeply about issues like nutrition and sustainable agriculture, these discriminating diners also seek to differentiate themselves from the unrefined eater, the common person who lives on junk food. Discriminating Taste argues that the rise of gourmet, ethnic, diet, and organic foods must be understood in tandem with the ever-widening income inequality gap. Offering an illuminating historical perspective on our current food trends, S. Margot Finn draws numerous parallels with the Gilded Age of the late nineteenth century, an era infamous for its class divisions, when gourmet dinners, international cuisines, slimming diets, and pure foods first became fads. Examining a diverse set of cultural touchstones ranging from Ratatouille to The Biggest Loser, Finn identifies the key ways that "good food" has become conflated with high status. She also considers how these taste hierarchies serve as a distraction, leading middle-class professionals to focus on small acts of glamorous and virtuous consumption while ignoring their class's larger economic stagnation. A provocative look at the ideology of contemporary food culture, Discriminating Taste teaches us to question the maxim that you are what you eat.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aFood consumptionxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aFood consumptionzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aFood habitsxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aFood habitszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aFoodxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aMiddle classzUnited StatesxSocial life and customs. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Pilot eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311066330308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2017z978311066609008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2017-2018z978311065742540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813576886423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813576886.jpg  aPDA5EBK  a978-3-11-065742-5  RUP eBook-Package 2017-2018c2017d2018  a97